            "<p><strong>Investigation 2</strong></p><p><strong>Using Ratios to Solve Problems</strong></p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "vSqJ3rNW9nyq034b",
        "title": "Text 1",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>In Investigation 1, we used ratios to compare quantities. The ratio statements in Investigation 1 were written as &quot;for every&quot; or &quot;to&quot; statements. Ratios can be written in many ways. For example:</p><ul><p>10 students prefer cheese pizza <strong>for every</strong> five who prefer pepperoni pizza.</p><p>The ratio of students who prefer cheese to pepperoni is 10 <strong>to</strong> 5.</p></ul><ul><p>                                  10 cheese <strong>for</strong> 5 pepperoni</p><p>                                  10 cheese <strong>per</strong> 5 pepperoni</p><p>                                  10 cheese <strong>to</strong> 5 pepperoni</p><p>                                    10 cheese <strong>:</strong> 5 pepperoni</p><p>                                                    or simply </p><p>                                                          10 <strong>:</strong> 5</p><p>In this investigation, we will continue to explore ratios and find ways to determine and use equivalent ratios.</p></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
